  <div class="content">
    <div class="content-basic-wrapper basic-sidebar clearfix">
    <header class="content-header basic-sidebar"><div class="panel-pane pane-panels-mini pane-node-header" >
  
                
  
  <!--<div class="pane-content">-->
    <div class="content-onecol one-col" id="mini-panel-node_header">
    <div><div class="panel-pane pane-primary-channel" >
  
                
  
  <!--<div class="pane-content">-->
    <div class="primary-channel-eyebrow"><a href="/tags/science">Science</a></div>  <!--</div>-->

  
  </div>
<h1>ZMapp: The Experimental Ebola Treatment Explained</h1>

  <div class="field-subtitle">
    <p>How tobacco may help defeat one of the worldâ€™s deadliest viruses.</p>
  </div>
<div class="panel-pane pane-byline" >
  
                
  
  <!--<div class="pane-content">-->
    <span class="author"><span class="label">By</span>
  
    <a href="/popsci-authors/lois-parshley" typeof="Concept" property="prefLabel" datatype="">Lois Parshley</a>  
</span> <span class="date" data-timestamp="1407528000"><span class="label">posted</span> Aug 8th, 2014 at 4:00pm</span>  <!--</div>-->

  
  </div>
</div>
</div>
  <!--</div>-->

  
  </div>
<div class="panel-pane pane-block pane-post-social-post-social-block" >
  
                
  
  <!--<div class="pane-content">-->
        <div class="postButtons" style="float:left;"></div>
    <a href="#" class="customIcon pw-widget-customIcon" name="customIcon">
      <img typeof="foaf:Image" alt="" src="/sites/popsci.com/modules/bonnier/sandcastle/images/placeholder.gif" data-src="http://www.popsci.com/sites/popsci.com/modules/bonnier/post_social/theme/post_icon_24.png" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" alt="" src="http://www.popsci.com/sites/popsci.com/modules/bonnier/post_social/theme/post_icon_24.png" /></noscript>
    </a>
    <span class="pw-counter-custom1">
      <span class="pw-button-counter_custom1">
        <b class="customCounter" style="font-weight: normal!important;">0</b>
      </span>
    </span>  <!--</div>-->

  
  </div>
</header>
  <article class="content-basic basic-sidebar">
    <div class="content-main basic-sidebar"><div class="panel-pane pane-entity-field pane-node-body" >
  
                
  
  <!--<div class="pane-content">-->
    
  <div class="field-body">
    <p><div class="media media-element-container media-default full-width"><img class="full-width" style="" typeof="foaf:Image" width="1000" height="750" alt="" src="/sites/popsci.com/modules/bonnier/sandcastle/images/placeholder.gif" data-smsrc="http://www.popsci.com/sites/popsci.com/files/styles/small_1x_/public/import/2014/800px-Tabac-Dordogne_02.JPG?itok=hv7Hafb5" data-medsrc="http://www.popsci.com/sites/popsci.com/files/styles/medium_1x_/public/import/2014/800px-Tabac-Dordogne_02.JPG?itok=SaIfPhcE" data-lgsrc="http://www.popsci.com/sites/popsci.com/files/styles/large_1x_/public/import/2014/800px-Tabac-Dordogne_02.JPG?itok=JOpWk7o8" /><noscript><img class="full-width" style="" typeof="foaf:Image" width="600" height="450" alt="" src="http://www.popsci.com/sites/popsci.com/files/styles/medium_1x_/public/import/2014/800px-Tabac-Dordogne_02.JPG?itok=SaIfPhcE" /></noscript>
  <div class="field-credit">
    <p><a href="http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Tabac-Dordogne_02.JPG#mediaviewer/File:Tabac-Dordogne_02.JPG">Wikimedia Commons</a></p>
  </div>

  <div class="field-body">
    <p>A tobacco field</p>
  </div>
</div></p>

<p>Last Saturday in Monrovia, Liberia, neighbors stood in the street trying to block officials as the Liberian Ministry of Health brought <a href="http://www.frontpageafricaonline.com/index.php/news/2531-deadly-virus-victims-bodies-left-unburied-in-johnsonville">37 bodies</a> of Ebola victims to a small plot of recently purchased land. In the midst of the burial, the excavator failed, leaving a few gaping holes in the ground and a pile of plastic covered shrouds. The bodies were left in open pits filled with water until Sunday, when a new delivery of cadavers was set to arrive. Plastic gloves and other equipment used during the burials were abandoned nearby, putting the townâ€™s residents at risk of infection.</p>

<p>Ebola is one of the worldâ€™s most lethal diseases, causing vomiting, kidney and liver failure, and hemorrhagic bleeding. The fatality rate is up to <a href="http://www.who.int/csr/disease/ebola/en/">90 percent</a>, and thereâ€™s currently no cure. Infection is spread by direct contact with animals or people who have the disease, which is why proper quarantine methods are so important. Unfortunately, as the burial scene in Monrovia last weekend demonstrates, health officials have struggled to contain the disease.</p>

<h6>The virus is "moving faster than our efforts to control it."</h6>

<p>Over the last several weeks, an outbreak that started in Guinea in March has spread to Liberia, Nigeria, and Sierra Leone. More than 1,700 people have been infected, and the crisis ballooned last week, killing 170 people in just nine days. The virus is "moving faster than our efforts to control it," <a href="http://www.who.int/csr/disease/ebola/en/">said</a> Dr. Margaret Chan, the director of the World Health Organization. If the situation continues to get worse, she said, the consequences could be "catastrophic."</p>

<p>Deaths in the medical community have heightened the growing fear of the disease. Dr. Kent Brantly, an American physician who was working at Liberiaâ€™s Ebola Consolidated Case Management Center, is one of the most recent doctors to contract the disease. Heavily dressed in a gown, an apron, three pairs of gloves, a hood covering his strawberry-blonde hair, and green plastic protective eyewear, Brantly looked vaguely alien as he bent over patientsâ€™ beds. But all that gear didnâ€™t keep him safe.</p>

<p>Shortly after Brantly tested positive, an American nurse, Nancy Writebol, was also diagnosed. Writebol was in charge of the wash-down station in the <a href="http://www.elwaministries.org/AreasofMinistry/Hospital/tabid/59/Default.aspx">ELWA Hospital</a>â€™s 20-bed unit for Ebola patients. In the wash station, workers are sprayed with a chlorine solution, which is meant to decontaminate people entering and leaving the isolation ward. Neither Brently nor Writebol are sure just where they were exposed.</p>

<p><div class="media media-element-container media-default full-width"><img class="full-width" style="" typeof="foaf:Image" width="1000" height="862" alt="" src="/sites/popsci.com/modules/bonnier/sandcastle/images/placeholder.gif" data-smsrc="http://www.popsci.com/sites/popsci.com/files/styles/small_1x_/public/import/2014/14440817981_ec46c31212_o%20%281%29.jpg?itok=ZCnAnkJK" data-medsrc="http://www.popsci.com/sites/popsci.com/files/styles/medium_1x_/public/import/2014/14440817981_ec46c31212_o%20%281%29.jpg?itok=wGK-MdGI" data-lgsrc="http://www.popsci.com/sites/popsci.com/files/styles/large_1x_/public/import/2014/14440817981_ec46c31212_o%20%281%29.jpg?itok=xKzS-AkM" /><noscript><img class="full-width" style="" typeof="foaf:Image" width="600" height="517" alt="" src="http://www.popsci.com/sites/popsci.com/files/styles/medium_1x_/public/import/2014/14440817981_ec46c31212_o%20%281%29.jpg?itok=wGK-MdGI" /></noscript>
  <div class="field-credit">
    <p><a href="https://www.flickr.com/search?sort=relevance&amp;license=4%2C5%2C6&amp;text=ebola">Flicker CC by 2.0</a></p>
  </div>

  <div class="field-body">
    <p>Ebola virus particles (blue) budding from a chronically infected VERO E6 cell (yellow-green).</p>
  </div>
</div></p>

<p>As news spread of the death of Samuel Brisbane, one of Liberiaâ€™s leading Ebola doctors, Brantly was evacuated in a special isolation plane back to the Dobbins Air Force Base in Georgia. Before leaving Liberia, in one of those strange twists of fate, heâ€™d received a blood infusion from one of his 14-year-old patients who had survived the disease. The young boy, â€œwanted to be able to help the doctor that saved his life,â€ Brantlyâ€™s employer <a href="http://www.samaritanspurse.org/article/samaritans-purse-doctor-serving-in-liberia-west-africa-tests-positive-for-ebola/">said.</a> There are tentative findings to suggest blood transfusions from survivors may provide new patients helpful antibodies, but the strategy hasnâ€™t been <a href="http://jid.oxfordjournals.org/content/179/Supplement_1/S18.short">thoroughly tested</a>.</p>

<p>Writebol was also given an experimental procedure, a dose of an untested serum. Initially there was only enough of the drug for one patient, and Brantly insisted it go to Writebol, who was in worse condition, but heâ€™s since been treated with the drug also. Raising the question of who has access to top-quality care, <a href="http://www.popsci.com/article/science/how-two-americans-got-untested-ebola-treatment">the Americans are the only two patients who have been given the medicine</a>, which had previously only been tested in lab animals.</p>

<p>The drug, ZMapp, is actually the collaboration between an American company, Mapp Biopharmaceutical, and a Canadian company funded by the Public Health Agency of Canada, who were working on similar projects when the outbreak hit. Mapp employs just nine people and has been financed only by the U.S. government, but theyâ€™re trying to figure out how to scale up quickly. Larry Zeitlin, Mappâ€™s president, <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/07/business/an-obscure-biotech-firm-hurries-ebola-treatment.html?action=click&amp;contentCollection=Health&amp;region=Footer&amp;module=MoreInSection&amp;pgtype=Blogs">told</a> the <em>New York Times,</em> â€œWe are discussing with the FDA the right path to make the drug available as quickly as possible.â€</p>

<p>ZMapp itself is made up of proteins called monoclonal antibodies, which bind to the Ebola virus rendering it harmless. The drug is made by infecting mice with a protein from the Ebola virus, and then modifying the miceâ€™s antibodies to more closely resemble human ones.</p>

<p>The results then need to be produced in large volumes, so scientists have turned to an interesting ally: plants.  A gene from the modified antibodies is introduced to the leaves of tobacco plants, via a system developed by <a href="http://www.freepatentsonline.com/8624080.html">Icon Genetics</a>. The leaves then produce the intended monoclonal â€œplantibodyâ€ proteins. It only takes about a week before the leaves can be harvested and the protein extracted and purified. Plus, itâ€™s inexpensive compared to the traditional method of growing these genetically modified mouse cells in labs.</p>

<p>Currently, these modified antibodies are being grown in Kentucky tobacco plants by the tobacco company Reynold American. (Other industry giants, like <a href="http://www.cantechletter.com/2013/07/medicago0712/">Philip Morris</a>, are also investing in medical plant-based technology.) â€œPharming,â€ as the process is known, is particularly useful because itâ€™s easier to produce proteins in higher volumes. â€œIt is grown in a greenhouse, and you can manufacture kilograms of the materials,â€ Erica Ollmann Saphire, a professor at the Scripps Research Institute <a href="http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/08/06/us-health-ebola-tobacco-idUSKBN0G607J20140806">told</a> <em>Reuters.</em></p>

<p><div class="media media-element-container media-default full-width"><img class="full-width" style="" typeof="foaf:Image" width="1000" height="667" alt="" src="/sites/popsci.com/modules/bonnier/sandcastle/images/placeholder.gif" data-smsrc="http://www.popsci.com/sites/popsci.com/files/styles/small_1x_/public/import/2014/ebola-response-7.jpg?itok=Obs4fTzI" data-medsrc="http://www.popsci.com/sites/popsci.com/files/styles/medium_1x_/public/import/2014/ebola-response-7.jpg?itok=ec_cyTs2" data-lgsrc="http://www.popsci.com/sites/popsci.com/files/styles/large_1x_/public/import/2014/ebola-response-7.jpg?itok=r2DY8zJh" /><noscript><img class="full-width" style="" typeof="foaf:Image" width="600" height="400" alt="" src="http://www.popsci.com/sites/popsci.com/files/styles/medium_1x_/public/import/2014/ebola-response-7.jpg?itok=ec_cyTs2" /></noscript>
  <div class="field-credit">
    <p>Courtesy of <a href="http://www.samaritanspurse.org/our-ministry/newsroom/#photos">Samaritanâ€™s Purse</a></p>
  </div>

  <div class="field-body">
    <p>A doctor with Samaritan's Purse working with Ebola patients.</p>
  </div>
</div></p>

<p>But there are some challenges in scaling up the serum production, starting with the fact that clinical trials havenâ€™t been run, and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) still hasnâ€™t approved the procedure. Plus, four out of seven monkeys treated with ZMapp in a trial last year still died of Ebola. How quickly the plantibodies can be produced also depends on Reynolds American, which may need several months to expand their facilities; the tobacco plants have to mature for about a month before theyâ€™re suitable for the procedure.</p>

<p>This frenzy highlights a significant problem with the way pharmaceutical research and development currently works: Because Ebola was so rare, there wasnâ€™t a financial incentive for big companies to work on finding a cure before this outbreak occurred. Many more may perish before the serum comes online.</p>

<p>In the meantime at least, both Brantley and Writebolâ€™s conditions are improving. Dr. Sanjay Gupta, CNNâ€™s chief medical correspondent and an assistant professor of neurosurgery at Emoryâ€™s School of Medicine, <a href="http://globalpublicsquare.blogs.cnn.com/2014/08/03/gupta-were-going-to-see-ebola-around-the-world/">said</a> he thought the outbreak would continue to spread, adding, â€œWe are going to see Ebola around the world.â€ But he thinks in the U.S. and other developed countries, it should be containable, an opinion the CDC <a href="https://twitter.com/CDCgov/statuses/495360909280563200">echoes.</a></p>

<p>As Liberia totters toward renewed violence and Nigeria declares a state of emergency, the question is what will happen in the rest of the worldâ€”emphasizing how different access to medical care can be.</p>
  </div>
  <!--</div>-->

  
